      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({(sharesOutstanding / 1000).toFixed(2)}B) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Abbott is a diversified healthcare leader. While COVID testing revenues have evaporated, its medical devices (like FreeStyle Libre) continue to grow impressively. An 8% FCF growth assumption models stable, low-double-digit medical device growth blended with mature pharma and nutritional segments.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Abbott's highly diversified, recession-resistant portfolio warrants a lower required rate of return compared to volatile tech stocks. At 8.5%, we demand a fair premium over risk-free rates for an established dividend aristocrat.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">{(growthRateTerminal * 100).toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is ~3%. Abbott provides essential medical devices, diagnostics, and nutrition. We assume it simply paces the broader economy forever, maintaining its market share in healthcare without wildly outgrowing the demographic trends.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

